To calculate the interest rate to be used, we will divide the 9% discount rate by the number of days in a year since its compounded daily.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Interest rate compounded daily} &= \dfrac{0.09}{365}
\\[10pt]
&=  0.000247\text{ or 0.025\%}
\end{aligned}$$

Hence, in calculating the present value of the investment, we will use the discount rate of 0.025%.

Next, considering the calculated daily rate and period on the previous steps, we will now compute the present value of the investment.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Present Value} &=\dfrac{\$80,000}{\left(1 +  0.00025 
\right)^{3650}}
\\[10pt]
&=\dfrac{\$80,000}{ 2.46}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$32,529.18}
\end{aligned}$$

**Based on our calculation, the present value of the investment is $32,529.18.**
